In theory, this should be it's own project. Because of the API required to be exposed per the assignment description
being very string-oriented, and my want to have a more type-safe API, I decided to implement said API, and then use
wrappers to convert between the string-based API and the type-safe API. This way, I can have the best of both worlds,
and I can also easily test the type-safe API without having to worry about the string parsing.

However, this creates the need to separate out the normally in-line conversion functions. This would normally be fine,
except that we can't create a new project in the solution to hold these functions, per the assignment description.

> As always, don't reference any projects not mentioned here.

To solve this problem, I decided to create a new folder called "Cell" in the Formula project, which handles converting
to and from cell references, cell data, cell ranges, et cetera, et cetera. This makes me deeply unhappy, but it's the
best solution I could come up with given the constraints of the assignment.

The reason this isn't in "Spreadsheet," where it would likely fit better, is because this would create a circular
dependency between the two projects, which is something I want to avoid at all costs. The Cell folder is a bit of a
hack, but it allows me to keep the type-safe API in the Formula project, while still being able to expose the
string-based API required by the assignment description.
